## Updated onboarding flow for VSCode extension

### Important note \- IN DRAFT

1. Please review these screens and adjust as needed, including the overall flow. This is intended to be directional and a draft\!
2. More thought has been put into the flow than the text, which is rough
3. Ignore the awful mocked-up logo, please\!

### Initial load of extension

This is the first screen users will see after installing or resetting the extension.

There are two variations to help guide the user to what they should do.

#### No open folder or session history

This screen helps users to either open a folder (if possible from an extension) or kick off a fun visual project. The top two buttons (“Open Folder”, “Clone Repository”) are highlighted as delivering value to one of their projects is likely to be more impactful than a fun toy.

If a user clicks “Open Folder” if could pop the VSCode Open Folder dialog.

If user clicks “Clone Repository" it could ask them for a URL or description of the repository, plus the folder to clone into. If a description is provided, the model can attempt to find it or ask for clarification. Once it’s cloned, we may want to re-open the folder in that workspace, if that is a clean experience so that the permissions are correct.  
![][image1]

#### Open folder but no session history

Contextual content, and prompts are useful for an existing project.

![][image2]

### Session history

Just show the usual screen, get them working\!

We could consider adding a sign in link to explore additional Kilo features as an added improvement, like cloud agents, etc.

### Paid model is selected

If a user selects a paid model, this is a good opportunity to get them further set up.

There are two variants, one for models which we have subscription support for, and those that don’t. This better guides users to the right configuration for themselves and makes it easy to discover the options in clear language. (No talk of providers, etc.)

#### User selected a paid model without supported subscription

If a user selects a paid model, we can then prompt them to create an account or login. The less emphasized option can take them to the provider settings.  
![][image3]

#### User selected a paid model which we support subscriptions for

![][image4]

### User hits anonymous rate limit

If a user hits the anonymous free rate limit, we should just ask them to create an account to keep going. This can be done in the chat window, as that is where they are already working.

This does not say they are specifically rate limited, just that they need to login or wait (some time period).
